node.text:
Idk why we made this. A couple days ago we were bored so we went to the thrift store, bought some costumes and decided to make a retro spy movie like a bunch of kids. 
No script, no plan, just inventing the movie as we filmed it, and having a damn good time doing it. 
We had the song on repeat, playing on a speaker the entire time we filmed. 
I hope you enjoy this random little movie hahahaha
@rachienoe @annieemacintosh @_wileyjr

node.text:
This is a passion project of mine that has been in the works since the beginning of Covid lockdown. I began writing the script last march- slowly adding to it day by day… Sending it to friends, getting feedback, and changing things around. 
I wanted @chelseakauai to be in it because she is always telling me beautiful stories like this one. @moore_rachel was kind enough to let us shoot on her sailboat while also being the perfect balance to Chelsea in the film. 
Acting is about subtlety and I think they both did an incredible job… it’s not easy with dialogue scenes. 
As for the footage, my goal was to NOT use any stock-footage. I spent most of the last year with this project in the back of my mind- always keeping an eye out for shots I could capture to help tell the story of Nasa’s Voyager Spacecrafts. 
@getter.sendy and I brainstormed concepts for VFX shots in the film, and being the incredibly talented human that he is, decided to try learning 10 years of VFX and compositing in just a few months. All the VFX shots of the spacecraft were done by him for the film based on storyboards we created. 
Other friends of mine helped me with the shots I was unable to capture- such as the volcanoes in Guatemala and the elephants in South Africa. 
One of my best friends @srfrmusic spent almost a whole year recording sound effects and making an incredible library of original sounds used in this film. 
I guess what I’m trying to say is: creating projects that are meaningful to you, is always made better when you surround yourself with a crew of talented, inspiring, and creative people. And in this case, I feel very lucky to call them my friends. 
Thank you friends for putting up with my creative vision, and bringing your full creative energy to make it possible. 

Can’t wait for the next one.

node.text:
Storytelling with images. 
In this episode of @creatorcircuit, I go through my process of telling a story while on a trip with friends in the Rockies. 

Each episode of Creator Circuit is 5 mins or less, covering a range of different topics in photography, videography, business, social media, collaboration and lifestyle. 
Each episode is on 1 specific topic to ensure you understand the concept fully. 
We have over 230+ videos on the site and we’re adding more regularly (4 more videos are going up today). 
Welcome to Creator Circuit!

node.text:
Headphones Recommended

This is the first short film I’ve made in quite a while and I’m super excited to share it. @chelseakauai and I spent 17 days in French Polynesia filming this video. The first half of the trip felt like an uphill battle. Everything we tried shooting didn’t feel “right” and we were feeling pretty uninspired, even in one of the most beautiful places on earth. 
In a wave of creativity and energized focus, Chelsea and I came up with the concept for ‘Lady of the Sea’ and excitedly wrote the beginnings of the narrative down in my journal. 
The moment Chelsea got in the water wearing the dress, we knew this would be a pretty unique project.

What lessons has the ocean taught you?

node.text:
A few weeks ago, @haydenkortemoore, @ryan.j.harris and I decided to go on a road trip through part of Vancouver island for 8 days. We rented a camper van and lived in it together. 
This video follows our experience as we disconnected from our busy lives for a bit. 
So I encourage to take 3 mins of your busy life and slow down to watch this. 
@srfrmusic & @ryan.j.harris wrote an original song for the video too which is pretty cool... 

The goal of our trip was to distill our lives down to their simplest components in order to create a deeper human connection with each other. 

I spent the week having an absolute blast. Even though we were all squished inside a van, I had some of the best sleeps of my life. Screen-time was an at an all-time low while laughter was at an all-time high. 

Thank you @corona for making this trip possible, and for being receptive to our creative vision. 
And special thanks to @tyler_ravelle for being so helpful on the ground.

node.text: A perfectly clear night under the Milky Way from the top of panorama ridge. You can see the orange glow of Vancouver on the horizon. After shooting star photos all night, @tobin_sparling and I hiked down at 4am to get to Garibaldi lake for sunrise. Sometimes the sleepless nights are worth it for not only the photos but also the memories.

A perfect lagoon on one of the islands surrounding Coron, Philippines.

node.text:
William Partois Ole Santian is a Maasai senior elder. We had the pleasure of sitting down with him for dinner and talking about his incredible life and his work that has lead the Masai tribe to better education and conservation knowledge.
The next day he guided us through the Mara where we saw a Leopard hunt and kill an Impala. Such an incredible experience.

node.text:
#shotoniphone 🙌🏼 It’s world photography day! One of the best pieces of advice I’ve gotten as a photographer is “the best camera is the one that’s with you”. I shot all of these photos on my iPhone (the 12 Pro Max and the 11 Pro). Almost all of these were quick moments of unexpected beauty where I only had the camera that’s in my pocket at the time. Here are a few tips for iPhone photography:

1. It’s all about the composition. An engaging composition draws your viewer into the image. Look for leading lines, rule of thirds, centre weighted, etc.

2. Shoot into the light. This one is a personal preference, but I always try to shoot into the light because it gives your images a dreamy glow and a really nice backlit effect. This works for both portraits and landscapes!

3. Shoot in DNG RAW if you have an iPhone 12, or use other photography apps that allow your phone to shoot in RAW. The Lightroom camera app allows older iPhones to shoot in RAW for example. This will give you much more freedom while editing.

I hope these tips helped with your iPhone photography! Remember, the best camera is the one that’s with you.

@apple
